		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper17</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>Declarative Name Binding and Scope Rules</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/GabriëlKonat.html">Gabriël Konat</a>, <a href="../profile/LennartCLKats.html">Lennart C. L. Kats</a>, <a href="../profile/GuidoWachsmuth.html">Guido Wachsmuth</a>, <a href="../profile/EelcoVisser.html">Eelco Visser</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_18">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_18</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Name binding and scoping are central static-semantics concerns, and the paper provides a compile-time resolution approach.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It introduces a declarative meta-language for specifying name binding rules in reusable, language-parametric terms.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> Integration into the Spoofax Language Workbench and support for editor services position it squarely as a tooling contribution.
</li></ul></li></ul>
